--- [RESPONSE] (7.4s) ---
### File Structure
```
CarRental/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── vehicle_search.html
│   ├── vehicle_details.html
│   ├── booking.html
│   ├── insurance_options.html
│   ├── rental_history.html
│   ├── reservations.html
│   ├── special_requests.html
│   └── locations.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (vehicle and UI images)
│
└── data/
    ├── vehicles.txt
    ├── customers.txt
    ├── locations.txt
    ├── rentals.txt
    ├── insurance.txt
    └── reservations.txt
```

### File Descriptions
```
app.py
- The main backend Python file containing the entire Flask (or similar Python web framework) application logic.
- Handles routing for all nine pages, data reading/writing from/to local text files in the 'data' directory.
- Implements business logic for searching vehicles, booking rentals, managing reservations, viewing rental history, selecting insurance, and handling special requests.
- Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into one file simplifies maintenance and deployment.

templates/
- Contains HTML template files for each of the nine pages defined in the requirements.
- Each HTML file corresponds to a page (e.g., dashboard.html for the Dashboard Page).
- Templates use IDs and elements as specified to ensure UI consistency and ease of frontend-backend integration.

static/
- Holds static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files, and images.
- css/styles.css: Styles for the entire web application.
- js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity, such as button actions and dynamic UI updates.
- images/: Vehicle images and other UI-related graphics.

data/
- Stores all application data in text files as specified.
- vehicles.txt, customers.txt, locations.txt, rentals.txt, insurance.txt, reservations.txt: Data files formatted according to the provided schema.
- The backend reads from and writes to these files to persist application state without a database.
```
